05665nam a22007095i 9781554582464DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545824647 a10.51644/97815545824642doi  a(DE-B1597)667410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1993.5 G3bC553 2012 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430943/09051122300aCinema and Social Change in Germany and Austria /ced. by James M. Skidmore, Gabriele Mueller. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (314 p.) :b5 colour, 1 b/w  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Media Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tCinema of Dissent? -- tChallenging Viewing Habits -- tThe Counter-Cinema -- tThe Triumph of Hyperreality: -- tSubversions of the Medical Gaze: -- tReassessing And Consuming History -- tLiterary Discourse and Cinematic Narrative: -- tHeimat 3 -- tTroubled Parents, Angry Children: -- tCreative Chaos as Political Strategy -- t“Looking for an Old Man with a Black Moustache” -- tHaha Hitler! -- tQuestioning Collective Identities -- tGerman Fascination for Jews -- tBorder, Bridge, or Barrier? -- tThe Transnational Deutschkei -- tDiasporic Queers -- tAn Insider’s View -- tThe Construction of Reality: -- tFilmography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex -- tBooks in the Film+Media Studies Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the last decade, contemporary German and Austrian cinema has grappled with new social and economic realities. The “cinema of consensus,” a term coined to describe the popular and commercially oriented filmmaking of the 1990s, has given way to a more heterogeneous and critical cinema culture. Making the greatest artistic impact since the 1970s, contemporary cinema is responding to questions of globalization and the effects of societal and economic change on the individual. This book explores this trend by investigating different thematic and aesthetic strategies and alternative methods of film production and distribution. Functioning both as a product and as an agent of globalizing processes, this new cinema mediates and influences important political and social debates. The contributors illuminate these processes through their analyses of cinema’s intervention in discourses on such concepts as “national cinema,” the effects of globalization on social mobility, and the emergence of a “global culture.” The essays illustrate the variety and inventiveness of contemporary Austrian and German filmmaking and highlight the complicated interdependencies between global developments and local specificities. They confirm a broader trend toward a more complex, critical, and formally diverse cinematic scene. This book offers insights into the strategies employed by German and Austrian filmmakers to position themselves between the commercial pressures of the film industry and the desire to mediate or even attempt to affect social change. It will be of interest to scholars in film studies, cultural studies, and European studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture industry -- Austria -- History -- 21st century. 0aMotion picture industry -- Germany -- History -- 21st century. 0aMotion picture industryzAustriaxHistoryy21st century. 0aMotion picture industryzGermanyxHistoryy21st century. 0aMotion pictures -- Austria -- History -- 21st century. 0aMotion pictures -- Germany -- History -- 21st century. 0aMotion pictures and globalization -- Austria. 0aMotion pictures and globalization -- Germany. 0aMotion pictures and globalizationzAustria. 0aMotion pictures and globalizationz